Diabetes Prediction

The following data was taken from Kaggle at: https://www.kaggle.com/mathchi/diabetes-data-set

The information pertains to data collected by the National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases. All patients are female Pima Indians, which is a common heritage to assess the aetiology of diabetes due to very high prevalence rates. The data set comes with a series of variables related to diabetes diagnosis. A binary target variable is provided relating to a true diabetes test.

I will be using this largely to practice using the Reticulate package in R, which allows for transition between R and Python within a single R markdown workbook. I find this particularly useful as preprocessing and EDA is preferable in R, whereas machine learning is preferable in Python. I will provide guidance on doing so as we go along.

Over a third of the individuals were diagnosed with diabetes. Lets illustrate how the predictor variables relate to the outcome. It’s very possible that there are moderating variables in these relationships - for example, age may affect the BMI-risk relationship. Lets group some of these variables to explore more closely

# Age groups
df$Age_group<-as.factor(ifelse(df$Age>18 &df$Age<=30, 'Young',
                     ifelse(df$Age>30 & df$Age <=50, 'MidAged',
                            ifelse(df$Age>50 & df$Age<=65, 'MidElderly', 'Elderly'))))

# BMI groups (typical medical cut offs)
df$BMI_group<-as.factor(ifelse(df$BMI>0 &df$BMI<25, 'NormalWeight',
                     ifelse(df$BMI>=25 & df$BMI <30, 'Overweight',
                            ifelse(df$BMI>=30 & df$BMI<35, 'ObeseC1', 'ObeseC2'))))

Diabetes Pedigree function exploration

The Diabetes Pedigree function is a likelihood of diabetes based on family history and genetic factors.

Lets look at some physiological predictors by age and BMI groups. Note that it’s clear some people were not measured for some variables as values are assigned 0, we should change these to NA.

# Where the value is 0 in any of the physiological columns, replace with NA
df[, 2:6][df[, 2:6]==0] <- NA

Feature engineering

Lets use some domain knowledge on diabetes diagnosis. The American Diabetes Association and WHO states that fasting glucose >126 is one threshold for diagnosis, and 110-125 is considered pre-diabetes, so we’ll generate this variable.

# Merge the variables we removed during imputation back in
knn_df<-df%>%dplyr::select(ID, Age_group, BMI_group, Outcome)%>%merge(knn_df, ., by='ID')

knn_df$glucose_threshold<-as.factor(ifelse(
  knn_df$Glucose < 110, 0,
  ifelse(knn_df$Glucose>= 110 & knn_df$Glucose < 126, 1, 2)
))

HOMA-IR is a universally used insulin resistance score which compares insulin and glucose levels. It can be considered closely related to diabetes. Lets calculate the value from known formula.

knn_df$HOMA <- (knn_df$Insulin * knn_df$Glucose)/405

These values seem high (probably because of the units), but it is more the mathematical interaction between insulin and glucose we’re interested in.

Skin thickness is a marker of body fat (%), BMI is a similar metric but does not estimate fatness (is just a ratio between height and weight). There are differences in fatness at a given BMI. Therefore, we can create a ratio of these two variables which may provide further information. Evidence: https://www.researchgate.net/publication/259920627_Effects_of_Age_Gender_BMI_and_Anatomical_Site_on_Skin_Thickness_in_Children_and_Adults_with_Diabetes

knn_df$BMI_fatness<-knn_df$BMI / knn_df$SkinThickness

# But skin thickness is also associated with age

knn_df$BMI_fatness_age<-(knn_df$BMI / knn_df$SkinThickness)*knn_df$Age

Lastly, lets label encode the grouping variables

knn_df<-knn_df%>%mutate(Age_group=fct_relevel(Age_group, 'Young', 'MidAged', 'MidElderly', 'Elderly'),
                        BMI_group=fct_relevel(BMI_group, 'NormalWeight', 'Overweight', 'ObeseC1', 'ObeseC2'))
  
knn_df$Age_group<-as.integer(factor(knn_df$Age_group))
knn_df$BMI_group<-as.integer(factor(knn_df$BMI_group))

Next, we want to split this data set into train and test data. Typically, about 70-80% of the data is used to train the model. However, I note that one 2017 publication using this data set (see below) used only 20% data to train and 80% to test. To see if I can compare with their model performance, I will use this approach for now.

Diabetes Mellitus Affected Patients Classification and Diagnosis through Machine Learning Techniques (Mercaldo, 2017)

It is important to note that this paper does not mention imputation, and I believe that the original dataset they use is complete. Therefore, to match their performance we are relying on good imputation

Stacking

Lets see if we can stack some basic clf models to improve the performance. After we’ll consider tuning.

We’ll use RF and XGB as features in an LDA meta-clf.

RF = RandomForestClassifier(random_state = 42)
LD = LinearDiscriminantAnalysis()
XGB= GradientBoostingClassifier()

Define stack

stack = StackingCVClassifier(classifiers=[RF, XGB],
                            use_probas=True, # this will use probabilities of the 3 classifiers as meta-features in the meta-classifier model
                            meta_classifier=LD,
                            random_state=42)

Run stack

Accuracy: 0.72 (+/- 0.01) [LD]
Accuracy: 0.72 (+/- 0.04) [StackingClassifer]

Tuning

The stacking of classifiers doesnt add much. There isn’t much tuning capacity in LDA, but we can tune the XGB and RFs and see as if they operate as better models.

Lets run a random search on the RF. First, define grid.

from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV

n_estimators = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(start = 200, stop = 2000, num = 10)]
max_features = ['auto', 'sqrt']
max_depth = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(10, 110, num = 11)]
max_depth.append(None)
min_samples_split = [2, 5, 10]
min_samples_leaf = [1, 2, 4]
bootstrap = [True, False]
random_grid = {'n_estimators': n_estimators,
               'max_features': max_features,
               'max_depth': max_depth,
               'min_samples_split': min_samples_split,
               'min_samples_leaf': min_samples_leaf,
               'bootstrap': bootstrap}
